1 Question 1

Suppose you have a dataframe called students with three columns: name, age, and grade. Write a function called increase_grade that takes a dataframe and a percentage increase as input, and returns a new dataframe where the grade column has been increased by the specified percentage for all students.

# Sample dataframe
students <- data.frame(
  name = c("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"),
  age = c(20, 21, 22),
  grade = c(80, 75, 100)
)
# Defining a function that will take the grades from the dataframe and the percentage increase in grades as inputs and calculate the new grades
increase_grade <- function(grade,percentage_increase){
    new_grade <- students$grade * (1 + percentage_increase / 100)
  return(new_grade)
  }
percentage_increase <- 10
# Creating a new column in our dataframe that will store in itself new grades calculated by the function
students$new_grade <- increase_grade(students$grade, percentage_increase)
students
     name age grade new_grade
1   Alice  20    80      88.0
2     Bob  21    75      82.5
3 Charlie  22   100     110.0

2 Question 2

Create a function employee_performance_analysis that takes the two datasets as inputs and performs the following tasks:

Step1: Merge employee_data with performance_data based on the employee_id.

Step2: Calculate a new column performance_grade based on the following criteria:

If rating is greater than or equal to 4, assign âHighâ. If rating is between 3 and 4, assign âMediumâ. If rating is less than 3, assign âLowâ. Step3: Return the merged dataset with the added performance_grade column.

# Sample data for employee_data
employee_data <- data.frame(
  employee_id = c(101, 102, 103, 104, 105),
  name = c("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie", "David", "Eve"),
  department = c("HR", "Finance", "Marketing", "IT", "Operations")
)
# Sample data for performance_data
performance_data <- data.frame(
  employee_id = c(101, 102, 103, 104, 105),
  rating = c(4.5, 3.2, 2.9, 4.8, 3.7),
  bonus = c(1000, 800, 500, 1200, 900)
)
library("dplyr")

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
# Creating function that will take the two dataframes as an input
employee_performance_analysis <- function(employee_data, performance_data){
# Merging the two dataframes and assigning the new dataframe to a variable "merged"
 merged <- left_join(employee_data, performance_data, by = c("employee_id"))
# Creating an additional column within the new dataframe that will indicate whether the performance grade is high, low or medium
   merged <- mutate(merged, performance_grade = ifelse(rating >= 4, "High", ifelse(rating < 3, "Low", "Medium")))
  return(merged)}

employee_performance <- employee_performance_analysis(employee_data, performance_data)
employee_performance

3         103 Charlie  Marketing    2.9   500               Low
4         104   David         IT    4.8  1200              High
5         105     Eve Operations    3.7   900            Medium

3 Question 3

Create a function in R that calculates the number of days until the next holiday based on the current date.

dates_df <- data.frame(
  date_interest = c("2024-02-07", 
                    "2024-03-10", 
                    "2024-04-01")
)
# Creating a function that takes the above dates from the dataframe as an input
days_until_holiday <- function(date_interest){
# Defining the holidays
  holidays <- c("New Year's Day" = "2024-01-01",
              "Easter" = "2024-04-21",
              "Christmas" = "2024-12-25")
  # Turning the dates from our initial dataframe into the date variables
  date_interest <- as.Date (dates_df$date_interest, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
  # Sorting the holidays in order in which they come after our interest dates
  next_holiday <- which(as.Date(holidays)>date_interest)
  # Finding the closest holiday to our date, as it will have number 1 (minimum value) assigned to it
  closest_holiday <- min(next_holiday)
  # Calculating the distance in days between the closest holiday and each interest date
  until_closest_holiday<- as.integer(difftime(as.Date(holidays[closest_holiday]), date_interest, units = "days"))
  return(until_closest_holiday)
}
# Defining a new column within the dataframe that will include the calculated distance between the closest holiday and each interest date
dates_df$days_until_next_holiday<-days_until_holiday(dates_df$date_interest)
dates_df
  date_interest days_until_next_holiday
1    2024-02-07                      74
2    2024-03-10                      42
3    2024-04-01                      20

4 Question 4

Now add a new column in which you list what holiday that is

name_holiday <- function(date_interest){
    holidays <- c("New Year's Day" = "2024-01-01",
              "Easter" = "2024-04-21",
              "Christmas" = "2024-12-25")
  date_interest <- as.Date (dates_df$date_interest, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
  next_holiday <- which(as.Date(holidays)>date_interest)
  closest_holiday <- min(next_holiday)
  # Defining a variable "holiday" which will contain the name of the closest holiday for each date
  holiday<-names(holidays)[closest_holiday]
  return(holiday)
}
dates_df$holiday<-name_holiday(dates_df$date_interest)
dates_df
  date_interest days_until_next_holiday holiday
1    2024-02-07                      74  Easter
2    2024-03-10                      42  Easter
3    2024-04-01                      20  Easter

Create a scatterplot showing the relationship between life expectancy and urbanization in 1970

library("ggplot2")
library("ggthemes")
library("dplyr")

#Setting path
setwd("C:/Users/Sofija/Desktop/Computational Methods/Week4/Data")
#Step1: Loading the data
life_expectancy <- read.csv(file = './life-expectancy.csv')
urbanization <- read.csv(file = './share-of-population-urban.csv')
#Step2: Removing empty strings
life_expectancy2<-subset(life_expectancy, Code!="")
#Step3: Changing variable name
names(life_expectancy2)[names(life_expectancy2)=="Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical."]<-"life_exp"
#Step4: Keeping only relevant vars
life_expectancy3<-subset(life_expectancy2, selec=c("Entity", "Code", "Year", "life_exp"))
#Step5: Removing empty strings
urbanization2<-subset(urbanization, Code!="")
#Step6: Changing variable name
names(urbanization2)[names(urbanization2)=="Urban.population....of.total.population."]<-"urb"
#Step7: Keeping only relevant vars
urbanization3<-subset(urbanization2, selec=c("Code", "Year", "urb"))
#Step8: Performing a merge
final<-left_join(life_expectancy3, urbanization3, by = c("Code"="Code",
                                                         "Year"="Year"))
#Step9: Removing NAs
final2<-final[complete.cases(final), ]
# Defining a subset within the dataset that will be showing just 1970
final_1970<-subset(final2, Year==1970)
# Creating the graph
ggplot(data = final_1970, 
# Assigning the axes
  mapping = aes(x=urb, 
                y=life_exp))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se= FALSE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

8 Question 8

What can you say about the relationship between urbanization and life expectancy over time. Write 5 sentences.

# Overall, there has always been a positive relationship between urbanization and life expectancy. Both life expectancy and urbanization have been increasing from 1960 to 2021.The standard deviation was lower until around 1980, and then again from around 2015, while between those two years it was higher (which might indicate that the correlation between the two was weaker during the period). Over time, life expectancy has gone up in less urbanized countries also. In some less urbanized countries, life expectancy has been under 25 years before the 21st century, while in the most urbanized countries it went over 85 years in the last years.
